BLACK HILLS/KANSAS GAS UTILITY COMPANY, LLC STATEMENT OF OPERATING CONDITIONS APPLICABLE TO TRANSPORTATION SERVICE PURSUANT TO 18 C.F.R. SECTION 284.224
This Statement of Operating Conditions describes the administrative and operational policies and procedures of Black Hills/Kansas Gas Utility Company, LLC ("Transporter"), a local distribution company, regarding transportation service conducted for any eligible Shipper ("Shipper") in Kansas pursuant to Transporter's limited-jurisdiction blanket certificate of public convenience and necessity issued by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission ("FERC") pursuant to Section 284.224 of the FERC's regulations, 18 CFR Section; 284.224. This FERC certificate authorizes Transporter to engage in the transportation of natural gas in interstate commerce to the same extent and in the same manner that intrastate pipelines are authorized to engage in such transportation under Section 311(a)(2) of the Natural Gas Policy Act of 1978 ("NGPA"). It is the policy of Transporter to render such transportation services under written transportation service agreements ("Transportation Service Agreements") containing the terms and conditions generally acceptable to Transporter and in accordance with those additional terms and conditions set forth herein, executed after consideration of its existing commitments, pipeline design capacity, available pipeline capacity, points of receipt and delivery, and other factors deemed material by Transporter. This Statement of Operating Conditions does not apply to gas transportation or other services provided by Transporter subject to the jurisdiction of the Kansas Corporation Commission.
RATE SCHEDULE LARGE VOLUME TRANSPORTATION SERVICE (LVTS)
1. Availability
Service under this rate schedule is available to individually metered non-residential end-use or wholesale Shippers, whose annual usage is anticipated to exceed 9,000 Dth and do not use gas for irrigation pumping. This service is available in all service areas in Kansas.
2. Service Agreement
Each prospective Shipper under the LVTS rate schedule is required to execute a Service Agreement. Such Service Agreement shall specify the service(s) requested by Shipper, the method under which Shipper elects to be billed, and the term of the agreement.
3. Rate
The rates shall be as set forth on the Statement of Currently Effective Rates of this Statement of Operating Conditions.
4. General Terms and Conditions
Service hereunder is subject to the Terms and Conditions of this Statement of Operating Conditions. In case of a difference between the terms of the Service Agreement and the terms of this Statement of Operating Conditions, the Statement of Operating Conditions shall be applicable.
GENERAL TERMS AND CONDITIONS
1. Definitions
a. BALANCING - A Supplier or Shipper's obligation to cause its Deliveries to equal its net Receipts with due consideration given to the Lost and Unaccounted For, if applicable, and other allowable in-kind deductions.
b. CRITICAL DAY - Any day during which, in the sole judgement of the interstate pipeline, service is limited due to capacity constraints, operational problems, or any other cause. It shall be deemed an Operational Flow Order ("OFO") Day on Transporter's affected areas. Shipper notification shall be as determined by the pipeline; no additional communication by Transporter shall be required.
c. DAILY NOMINATION REQUIREMENT - The quantity of gas required to be delivered to Transporter at Receipt Point(s) for the account of Shipper in order to meet 1) Shipper's daily requirement for flowing gas (gas physically delivered to end-user(s)), 2) Losses, and 3) Correction of Shipper's Imbalance condition existing at the end of the preceding Gas Day.
d. DAILY SCHEDULING TOLERANCE - The maximum Imbalance quantity at the end of any Gas Day which Transporter will allow Shipper without additional charge. Shipper's Daily Scheduling Tolerance shall be determined as five percent (5%) of daily Nominations.
e. DAY - See GAS DAY.
f. DELIVERIES or DELIVERY - The quantity of gas delivered by Transporter to end-user for the account of Shipper.
g. DELIVERY POINT - The location where Transporter's gas distribution facilities are interconnected with the third-party's facilities. This location is where Shipper and Transporter have agreed that all or part of the Receipts for the account of Shipper will be transported and delivered by Transporter to the end-user for the account of Shipper.
h. GAS DAY - The twenty-four (24) hour period which begins at 9:00 a.m. Central Time and ends at 9:00 a.m. Central Time the following day.
i. LOSSES - The quantity of gas used and/or lost as part of Transporter's normal distribution system operation. Line loss charges will be Transporter's systemwide Lost and Unaccounted ("L&U") Account as listed on statement of rates and applied on a volumetric basis to the quantity of gas delivered to the end-user.
j. NOMINATION - The quantity of gas that Shipper requests to be received by Transporter at each Receipt Point and delivered to Shipper at each Delivery Point for a Gas Day. The quantity nominated must be equalized as far as practicable over the twenty-four (24) hour period and for the services provided hereunder is assumed to have been delivered to Transporter uniformly during each hour of the Gas Day.
k. OPERATIONAL BALANCING AGREEMENT - An agreement between Transporter and any party delivering gas into Transporter's system which describes the manner in which differences between actual Receipts into Transporter's system and nominated quantities into Transporter's system will be resolved between the parties.
l. OPERATIONAL FLOW ORDER - A notice issued by Transporter to Shipper(s) requiring the Delivery of specified quantities of gas to Transporter for the account of Shipper at times deemed necessary by Transporter to maintain system integrity and to assure continued service. An Operational Flow Order ("OFO") may be issued to the smallest affected area. For example, a single Receipt Point, Receipt Points on a pipeline, or the entire system. Notification shall be via Transporter's electronic bulletin board ("EBB"). Any Critical Day declared by the upstream pipeline is also an OFO Day on Transporter's affected area, but Shipper notification shall come from the upstream pipeline.
m. IMBALANCE - A condition where allocated daily and/or cumulative monthly Receipts fail to equal allocated daily and/or cumulative monthly Deliveries. A Positive (Excess) Imbalance condition exists when allocated daily and/or cumulative monthly Receipts exceed allocated daily and/or cumulative monthly Deliveries. A Negative (Deficiency) Imbalance condition exists when allocated daily and/or cumulative monthly Deliveries exceed allocated daily and/or cumulative monthly Receipts. When Shipper has an Imbalance, Transporter has either provided gas to Shipper to meet an Underage (Deficiency), or stored gas for Shipper to meet an Overage (Excess).
n. OVERAGE - An Imbalance condition where allocated daily and/or cumulative Receipts exceed allocated daily and/or cumulative Deliveries. This condition reflects the cumulative extent Receipts exceed Deliveries since Receipts and Deliveries were last in balance. A Positive (Excess) Imbalance condition is considered an Overage.
o. RECEIPTS - The quantity of gas actually received by Transporter for the account of Shipper at Receipt Point(s).
p. RECEIPT POINT - The location where Transporter physically receives gas delivered to Transporter for the account of Shipper. This location is the interconnection between Transporter and entity responsible for the Delivery of Shipper-owned gas to Transporter. The Receipt Point is usually physically located at the Town Border Station upstream of the Delivery Point. The Receipt Point must be a location physically connected by Transporter facilities to the Delivery Point. If Transporter can, operationally, contractually, and without adversely affecting the service to its other end-users, permit Shipper to use a Receipt Point which is not physically connected through Transporter facilities to the Delivery Point(s), Transporter may waive the Receipt Point restriction.
q. RECORDING EQUIPMENT - Equipment which is capable of obtaining, accumulating, and storing data regarding gas flow for intervals equal to or less than twenty-four (24) hours in duration.
r. SERVICE AGREEMENT - An agreement entered into between Transporter and Shipper, specifying the service(s) requested by Shipper, method of billing, and term of agreement.
s. SHIPPER - Any person, association, firm, public or private corporation, or any agency of the federal, state, or local government or legal entity who has entered into a Service Agreement with Transporter for the transportation of gas hereunder.
t. SHUTOFF - Service interruption initiated by Transporter, terminating service hereunder, to Shipper as a result of failure of Shipper to pay Transporter for service or as a result of unsafe conditions.
u. TELEMETRY - Equipment which is capable of obtaining, accumulating, and transmitting to a central location, real time data regarding the gas flow.
v. TRANSPORTATION SERVICE or TRANSPORTATION - The physical and/or contractual movement of Shipper-Owned gas through Transporter's distribution system from Receipt Point(s) to Delivery Point(s).
w. TRANSPORTER - The term "Transporter" is herein used to designate Black Hills/Kansas Gas Utility Company, LLC, which furnishes natural gas Transportation Service under these general terms and conditions.
x. UNDERAGE - An Imbalance condition where Deliveries exceed Receipts. This condition reflects the cumulative extent Deliveries exceed Receipts since Deliveries and Receipts were last in balance. A Negative (Deficiency) Imbalance condition is considered an Underage.
2. Application for Service and Agreements
Each prospective Shipper under the LVTS rate schedule is required to execute a Service Agreement.
Applications for service will be processed promptly by Transporter. Application for gas Transportation Service shall be made by Shipper to Transporter and upon acceptance of such application, Transporter shall as promptly as practicable supply Shipper with service in accordance with rates, rules, terms, regulations, and conditions herein. Regardless of billing arrangements elected by Shipper, they shall be responsible for payment for all service(s) provided.
3. Conditions of Service
To be considered for service, Applicants must agree to the following conditions:
a. To comply with all provisions of the line extension policy as described in Section 12 herein.
b. Load to be connected must not be prohibited by the construction policy of the pipeline supplier or be in violation of any end use standards or orders promulgated by State or Federal Agencies or as Transporter may establish in this Statement of Operating Conditions.
4. Balancing
a. Shipper shall have the obligation to balance gas receipts (transportation gas delivered to Transporter at the Receipt Point), with thermally equivalent gas Deliveries (transportation gas delivered by Transporter to Shipper at the Delivery Point(s)). The difference between cumulative allocated Receipts and cumulative allocated Deliveries is considered an Imbalance condition.
b. Upon termination of service hereunder, either the Shipper shall purchase or transport sufficient quantities of gas to satisfy any Underage quantities, or the Transporter shall purchase Shipper's Overage quantities. This purchase shall be completed in accordance with the provisions of Transporter's Monthly Cash Out Charges per Section 6 herein. In addition, Shipper shall be responsible for any other applicable charge(s) set forth in Transporter's Transportation Rate Schedules.
c. Delivery from systems with a single Receipt source will use the transporting entity's statement as to therms and heating value as conclusive. Delivery from systems with multiple Receipt sources shall be determined based on the heating value of the gas delivered to Shipper to determine the requirement for thermal balancing.
5. Telemetry
Shipper is responsible for costs associated with Transporter acquiring and installing Telemetry Equipment at the Delivery Point.
6. Other Transportation Charges
Transport Customers on the LVTS rate schedule are subject to the following charges in addition to the charges referenced in the Statement of Currently Effective Rates of this Statement of Operating Conditions:
a. Daily Imbalance Charges: A Daily Imbalance Charge shall apply to any Shipper served through Northern Natural Gas, Colorado Interstate Gas, Panhandle Eastern Pipeline, or any other pipeline that subsequently adopts daily scheduling charges, and whose Imbalance Condition exceeds the Daily Scheduling Tolerance. This Daily Imbalance Charge is applied to the daily quantities by which Shipper's Imbalance Condition exceeds Shipper's Daily Scheduling Tolerance. Actual daily Delivery quantities shall be used to determine the Imbalance Condition for Shippers with recording equipment or Telemetry. Estimated daily Delivery quantities shall be used to determine the Imbalance Condition for Shippers without recording equipment or Telemetry, or where such equipment malfunctions. Estimated daily Delivery quantities shall be determined by Transporter and may be based on available data including nominated quantities, meter readings, Shipper load characteristics, actual weather conditions, and other information. This Daily Imbalance Charge is accumulated and assessed monthly. For each pipeline, the FERC-approved charges apply. Revenues collected from Daily Imbalance Charges will be credited to the overall general system gas cost through the Transporter's cost of gas mechanism. The Daily Imbalance Charges and Daily Scheduling Tolerances for any Shipper served through Northern Natural Gas shall be the following:
1) Daily Scheduling Charges on Normal Days. On days without upstream limitations, Operational Flow Order or Critical Days, the following charges will be in effect:
a. A Daily Scheduling Tolerance of +/- 5% of confirmed nomination will be applied.
b. For Imbalances within tolerance, no Daily Scheduling Charges will be applied.
c. For Imbalances outside Daily Scheduling Tolerance, a Daily Scheduling Charge shall be applied to the quantity exceeding Daily Scheduling Tolerance equal to the Daily Delivery Variance Charge (DDVC) rate in Northern Natural Gas Company's currently effective FERC gas tariff.
2) Daily Scheduling Charges, System Overrun Limitation. On days the interstate pipelines, or Transporter, declare a System Overrun Limitation, or other Underage restriction, as defined in their tariff, the following charges will be in effect:
a. For an Underage, the following charges will be applied:
i. For consumption up to 105% of confirmed nomination, the greater of $1.00 or 1.25 multiplied by the highest published Platts "Gas Daily" Midpoint price on the applicable day at any of the applicable index points of: Field Area - Panhandle, Tx-Okla. and El Paso, Permian per Dekatherm in excess of confirmed nomination up to 105%.
ii. For consumption greater than 105% of confirmed nomination, the greater of $21.275 or 2.0 multiplied by the highest published Platts "Gas Daily" Midpoint price on the applicable day at any of the applicable index points of: Field Area - Panhandle, Tx-Okla. and El Paso, Permian per Dekatherm in excess of 105% of confirmed nomination.
b. For consumption less than the confirmed nomination, there is no charge.
3) Daily Scheduling Charges, System Underrun Limitation. On days the upstream pipelines, or Transporter, declare a System Underrun Limitation, or other Overage restriction, as defined in their tariff, the following charges will be in effect:
a. For consumption greater than the confirmed nomination, there is no charge.
b. For consumption less than the confirmed nomination, the greater of $1.00 or 1.25 multiplied by the highest published Platts "Gas Daily" Midpoint price on the applicable day at any of the applicable index points of: Field Area - Panhandle, Tx-Okla. and El Paso, Permian per Dekatherm.
4) Daily Scheduling Charges, Critical Days. On days the upstream pipelines, or Transporter, declare a Critical Day as defined in their tariff, the following charges will be in effect:
a. For consumption greater than the confirmed nomination, the following charges will be applied:
i. For consumption up to 102% of confirmed nomination, the greater of $15.00 or 1.5 multiplied by the highest published Platts "Gas Daily" Midpoint price on the applicable day at any of the applicable index points of: Field Area - Panhandle, Tx-Okla. and El Paso, Permian per Dekatherm in excess of confirmed nomination up to 102%.
ii. For consumption greater than 102% up to 105% of confirmed nomination, the greater of $22.00 or 1.75 multiplied by the highest published Platts "Gas Daily" Midpoint price on the applicable day at any of the applicable index points of: Field Area - Panhandle, Tx-Okla. and El Paso, Permian per Dekatherm in excess of 102% up to 105% of confirmed nomination.
iii. For consumption greater than 105% up to 110% of confirmed nomination, the greater of $56.50 or 2.0 multiplied by the highest published Platts "Gas Daily" Midpoint price on the applicable day at any of the applicable index points of: Field Area - Panhandle, Tx-Okla. and El Paso, Permian per Dekatherm in excess of 105% up to 110% of confirmed nomination.
iv. For consumption greater than 110% of confirmed nomination, the greater of $113.00 or 3.0 multiplied by the highest published Platts "Gas Daily" Midpoint price on the applicable day at any of the applicable index points of: Field Area - Panhandle, Tx-Okla. and El Paso, Permian per Dekatherm in excess of 110% of confirmed nomination.
b. For consumption less than the confirmed nomination, there is no charge.
On Critical Days Daily Imbalance Charges otherwise applicable shall be waived if Shipper is in an Overage condition. When Operational Flow Orders have been made, Daily Imbalance Charges otherwise applicable shall be waived if Shipper is in an Overage condition.
b. Unauthorized Delivery Charge: An Unauthorized Delivery Charge shall apply to Shipper(s) whose allocated Receipts are less than allocated Deliveries during a Critical Day or when an Operational Flow Order is imposed. This daily charge is accumulated and assessed monthly. This charge shall apply when Deliveries or Operational Flow Ordered quantities are in excess of Receipts.
The monthly charge shall be $20.00 per Dth per day on Operational Flow Order days. On Critical Days, Negative Imbalance conditions shall be charged as follows: Up to 5% of confirmed Nominations shall be charged at $20.00 per Dth. The remaining Negative Imbalance condition shall be charged at $113.00 per Dth.
If additional Deliveries to Shipper beyond those nominated are made which result in Transporter incurring pipeline charges or penalties, Transporter shall have the option to allocate such penalties and charges to Shipper on a basis determined by Transporter.
c. Unauthorized Receipt Charge: An Unauthorized Receipt Charge shall apply to Shippers whose allocated Deliveries are less than allocated Receipts in violation of an Operational Flow Order. This daily charge is accumulated and assessed monthly. This charge shall apply when Receipts or Operational Flow Ordered quantities are in excess of Deliveries. This charge shall be $20.00 per Dth per day on Operational Flow Order days.
If additional Receipts from Shipper beyond those nominated are made which result in Transporter incurring pipeline charges or penalties, Transporter shall have the option to allocate such penalties and charges to Shipper on a basis determined by Transporter.
d. Monthly Cashout Charges: At the end of each calendar month, Shipper is required to balance its allocated Receipts and allocated Deliveries. Any variance between Shipper's allocated Receipts and allocated Deliveries will result in the following "cash out" of imbalance volumes:
1) Northern Natural Gas Pipeline. For Shippers on Northern Natural Gas Pipeline the difference between allocated Receipts and allocated Deliveries will be charged or credited to Shipper based on the average of the highest, average of the lowest or average Platts Daily Price Survey Midpoint Gas Prices for Northern, demarc or Northern, Ventura for the month the Imbalance was incurred and based on tiering as set forth in Transporter's Tariff.
2) WTG Hugoton, LP. For Shippers on WTG Hugoton Pipeline, the difference between allocated Receipts and allocated Deliveries will be charged or credited to Shipper based on the highest, lowest or average Platts Daily Price Survey Midpoint Gas Prices for Panhandle, TX-Okla for the month the Imbalance was incurred and based on tiering as set forth in Transporter's Tariff.
3) ONEOK Field Services Company, LLC. For Shippers on ONEOK, the difference between allocated Receipts and allocated Deliveries will be charged or credited to Shipper based on the highest, lowest or average Platts Daily Price Survey Midpoint Gas Prices for Northern, demarc plus $1.15 for the month in which the Imbalance was incurred and based on tiering as set forth in Transporter's Tariff.
4) All Other Pipelines. For Shippers on all other pipelines, the difference between allocated Receipts and allocated Deliveries will be charged or credited to Shipper based on the average of the highest, average of the lowest or average Platts Daily Price Survey Midpoint Gas Prices off Panhandle, TX/Okla, Southern Star, NGPL Midcontinent, and CIG Rockies for the month the Imbalance was incurred and based on tiering as set forth in Transporter's Tariff.
e. Line Loss Charges: Line loss charges will be Transporter's systemwide Lost and Unaccounted ("L&U") Account as shown on the Statement of Rates, and applied on a volumetric basis to the quantity of gas delivered
f. Nomination Charge: The timetable for Nominations to Transporter can be found in Section 14 herein. A Nomination Charge shall apply to Shippers whose Nomination to Transporter's internet-enabled electronic bulletin board (EBB) is incorrect. The charge shall be $25.00 per occurrence. An occurrence is any time the confirmed pipeline Nomination and the Nomination in the EBB do not match. The Nomination Charge will not be assessed more than once in the same billing month. Charges will not be assessed due to pipeline allocation changes.
7. Optional Services
Shipper may choose to separately contract for services from Transporter that are approved by the Kansas Corporation Commission which best serve its needs.
8. Billing and Payment
1) Due Date
Bills shall be calculated in accordance with the rate schedule each month and shall be payable monthly.
All bills for service are due and payable upon receipt. A bill shall be deemed delinquent if payment thereof is not received by the utility or its authorized agent on or before the date stated on the bill which date shall be the twentieth (20th) day after date of billing. A late payment charge in an amount equal to two percent (2%) of the delinquent amount owed for current service will be added to the bill if payment is not received on or before the net due date stated on the bill.
2) Credit Worthiness and More Frequent Billing
Transporter reserves the right to evaluate a Shipper's financial condition at any time, including prior to initiating service, if circumstances warrant such review. If Transporter determines that Shipper's ability to pay bills may be in jeopardy because of a deteriorating financial condition, bill payments may be required more frequently than monthly. Shippers who become subject to more than monthly billing will be given at least twenty-four (24) hours written notice of such status.
Evidence of deteriorating bill-paying ability may be manifested but not limited to the following indications: (1) lowered ratings by credit agencies; (2) failure to pay an undisputed bill before the delinquency date for three consecutive billing periods; (3) a general knowledge of Shipper's worsening financial condition from information imparted by other suppliers and vendors; and, (4) newspaper and trade journal accounts.
If the Transporter bills Shipper more than once a month, such bills shall include only gas transportation through that billing date. Transporter will resume billing Shipper on a once-a-month basis when Transporter becomes satisfied that Shipper is no longer a credit risk.
9. Discontinuation of Service
a. Conditions Under Which Transporter May Refuse or Discontinue Service:
A. Failure to Comply: If Shipper fails to comply with or perform any of the obligations of its part, Transporter shall have the right to give Shipper written notice of Transporter's intention to terminate the Transportation on account of such failure, then Transporter shall have the right to terminate such Transportation at the expiration of five days after the giving of said notice unless Shipper shall make good such failure. Termination of such Transportation for any such cause shall be a cumulative remedy as to Transporter and shall not release Shipper from its obligation to make payment of any amount or amounts due or to become due from Shipper to Transporter under the applicable Schedule. In order to resume Transportation after termination of service hereunder, it shall be necessary for Shipper to reapply for service.
B. Nonpayment of Bills: Transporter may discontinue service upon ten (10) days written notice when Shipper's bill becomes delinquent, whether the bill is based on Shipper's meter reading, Transporter's meter reading or Transporter's estimate of service.
C. Dangerous Conditions Found on Shipper's Premises: In any case where Transporter has received notice or knows that a dangerous condition exists on Shipper's premises, Transporter may, without any advance notice, refuse to connect service if service has not already been started, or shut off the service and same shall not be resumed until such dangerous condition shall have been eliminated.
D. When Shipper violates any rule of Transporter which violation adversely affects the safety of Shipper or other persons, or the integrity of Transporter's Delivery system, Transporter need not provide Shipper notice prior to discontinuation under these circumstances.
E. If natural gas Transportation Service is disconnected for any of the reasons stated above, Transporter will require a Disconnection Charge of $15.00.
10. Shipper's Service Obligations
a. Shipper, upon written request, shall furnish Transporter such reasonable data, as in Transporter's judgment is necessary for the proper analysis of the Transportation requirements of Shipper.
b. Shipper shall arrange for the purchase of gas other than Transporter's supply and for the Delivery of such gas to a Receipt Point(s).
c. Unodorized mainline and gathering line large volume Transportation Shippers are responsible for the purchase and installation of the required odorizing equipment. Transportation Service will be discontinued to Shippers who fail to provide the required odorizing equipment. The required odorization equipment may be purchased and installed by Transporter. Shipper shall be responsible for the costs associated with Transporter acquiring and installing odorizing equipment.
d. Service as an LVTS is only available to individually metered non-residential end-use or wholesale customers, whose annual usage is anticipated to exceed 9,000dth and do not use gas for irrigation pumping.
e. In case gas is found by Shipper to be escaping from any pipes or equipment owned by Shipper, Shipper shall notify Transporter's office at once. In case of interruption of service, Shipper shall notify Transporter immediately.
f. Transporter may charge for all materials furnished and for all work done on Shipper's equipment. Transporter shall not charge for any costs of replacements or repairs to equipment furnished and owned by Transporter on Shipper's premises except when damage is due to negligence or misuse of Shipper or its agents.
g. Shipper will provide or procure for Transporter at Shipper's expense such right-of-way satisfactory to Transporter, across property owned or otherwise controlled by Shipper, for the construction, operation, and maintenance by Transporter of its facilities necessary or incidental to the natural gas Transportation Service.
11. Transporter's Service Obligations
a. Delivery pressure of natural gas by Transporter is expected to approximate four ounces. However, in no event shall delivery pressure for Shipper be less than two ounces or more than two pounds per square inch as measured at Shipper's meter outlet.
b. All Shipper-owned gas transported hereunder shall be of commercial quality. If the gas tendered for transportation is not of commercial quality or is gas which will adversely impact the gas stream of Transporter, said gas shall not be transported.
c. Transporter will use reasonable diligence in providing interruptible Transportation Service. Transporter will not be liable for damages for any interruption of service.
d. Transporter reserves the right to shut off Transportation of gas at any time when such action is necessary for the purpose of making repairs or in case of any emergency. In such case, Transporter shall make every reasonable effort to restore service at the earliest practical moment. An interruption of service will not relieve Shipper from any charges for service which have actually been rendered.
12. Measurement
a. All transport gas shall be measured on a Btu basis. Measurement shall be based on available information regarding quantities of gas received and delivered, pressure and temperature conditions, and energy content of the gas stream. Transporter shall determine the measurement equipment required to determine the Receipts and Deliveries of Shipper-owned gas transported hereunder.
b. Metering
1) Metering Basis:
A. Unit of Measurement: The cubic foot shall be the standard unit for measuring quantity. For purposes of testing, a cubic foot of gas shall mean that amount of gas contained in a volume of one cubic foot (dry), at sixty (60) degrees Fahrenheit at standard pressure (14.73 PSI), unless specified otherwise by contract. The British thermal unit shall be the standard unit for billing.
B. Heating Value: The average gross heating value of the gas will be at least 800 Btu per cubic foot on a dry basis. The gross heating value shall be determined as frequently as necessary for reasonably accurate determinations, by means of adequate apparatus.
C. Measurement Factors: The volume of gas delivered as measured at pipeline pressures shall be corrected to the unit of measurement. Measurement and determination of volumes delivered shall be made in accordance with the recommendations set forth in A.G.A. Gas Measurement Committee Reports as amended, revised, or superseded from time to time.
D. Temperature: The temperature of the gas passing through the meters shall be assumed to be sixty (60) degrees Fahrenheit. Where a recording thermometer has been installed to record the temperature of the gas flowing through the meters, the arithmetic average of the hourly temperature so recorded shall be used in measurement computation.
E. Specific Gravity: The specific gravity of the gas shall be determined as frequently as necessary for reasonably accurate determinations, by means of adequate apparatus and such gravity so obtained, shall be used in the measurement of gas.
F. Heat Content: The heat content of the gas shall be determined based on reasonably accurate determination and information regarding heat content of gas delivered by pipeline suppliers, calorimeters, and gas sampling.
2) Meters
A. Meter: The gas delivered by Transporter to Shipper shall be measured by an adequate meter of standard type, installed, operated, and maintained by Transporter at its sole expense.
B. Location of Meters: The meters and meter connections are the property of Transporter and may be removed when the service is terminated for any cause. All facilities owned by Shipper are subject to the approval of Transporter. Transporter shall provide periodic leak surveys and maintain cathodic protection on the respective service line.
C. Inspection by Transporter: Shippers shall permit employees and inspectors of Transporter, when properly identified, to enter their premises at reasonable hours to examine the piping, and other equipment relating to Transporter's service and to ascertain connected loads and make necessary tests.
D. Testing of Transporter's Meters: Transporter shall test its meters at reasonable intervals, not to exceed that specified by state regulation, and shall, at the time of the test, adjust the meter to record accurately.
In the event Shipper requests Transporter to test a meter, Shipper shall deposit with Transporter a Meter Test Fee of up to $50.00. If the meter is found to be within the accuracy limits (as set forth in Section 12.b.1), the entire Meter Test Fee will be retained in order to help defray Transporter's expense in testing the meter. In all other cases, the Meter Test Fee shall be refunded to Shipper.
E. Adjustment of Measurement Errors: Should any meter fail to register or register inaccurately and on test is found more than two percent in error, Transporter will refund to Shipper such percentage of the amount of the bill of Shipper for the period of such inaccuracy. If the period of inaccurate registration cannot be determined, Transporter will refund such percentage of the bill of Shipper for the period of six (6) months just previous to the removal of such meter from service, or for the time the meter was in service, not exceeding six (6) months, as the meter shall have been shown to be in error by such test.
If on test the meter is found to be more than two percent (2%) slow, Transporter may collect from Shipper the amount estimated to be due for Transportation Service not charged for in bills rendered but not to exceed the six-month period prior to such test.
If a meter is found not to register for any period, registers intermittently, or partially registers for any period, Transporter shall estimate a charge for the gas transported, but not metered, by averaging the amounts used over similar periods preceding or subsequent thereto or over corresponding periods in previous years.
13. Nomination
Shippers are required to nominate daily. All Nominations must be provided via Transporter's internet-enabled electronic bulletin board and must include quantities of gas to be transported by Receipt Point(s) and Delivery Point(s). All Nominations for the Timely and Evening cycles for next day gas flow are due as set forth on the table below:
Timely Timely Day-Ahead 1:00 PM Central Clock Time

Shippers requesting same day gas flow are subject to the intra-day Nomination cycles set forth below, and such requests will be accepted by Transporter on a best effort basis. In addition, as noted in the schedule set forth below, intra-day natural gas Nominations that have priority over other classes of service can displace or "bump" that flowing service, both scheduled and flowing Transportation, except as set forth below:

Transporter shall have the right to reject or change any Nomination that it deems is being made in order to take unfair advantage of any tariff provisions, including but not limited to, monthly cash outs.
The Transporter may provide for a final nomination cycle. A final nomination cycle will be provided only as supported by the interconnecting pipeline and the Transporter. The purpose of the final nomination cycle is to provide Shippers an opportunity to Balance nominations to best available usage for the day. This service will be provided in accordance with any other agreements mutually agreed to on the interconnecting pipeline or interconnecting points. The deadline for this cycle is the deadline required by the interconnecting pipeline.
The Shipper has the responsibility to notify the Transporter when final nomination cycle nominations are submitted for confirmation. The nomination cycle nominations must be agreed to by the Transporter and cannot cause harm to the Transporter.
14. Notification for Enrollment and Changes to Transport)
The Shipper shall notify Transporter of their intent to begin or change service to End-User under the applicable transportation rate schedules through the filing of an End User/Customer Transport Authorization Form or amendment thereto with Transporter.
15. Operational Balancing Agreement (OBA)
Transporter shall have the right, but not the obligation, to enter into an OBA with any party delivering gas into Transporter's system. Transporter shall, on a nondiscriminatory basis, determine which supplies necessitate an OBA. Nothing in any OBA shall limit Transporter's right to take any action that may be required to maintain system integrity.
16. Operational Flow Order Penalty
Shipper(s) who fail to deliver to Transporter for the account of Shipper(s) specified Operational Flow Ordered quantities of gas shall be billed appropriate Unauthorized Delivery Charges. Shipper(s) who repeatedly fail to deliver to Transporter specified Operational Flow Order quantities of gas will not be permitted to continue Transportation Service.
17. Recording and Telemetry Equipment
Transporter shall be allowed access for maintaining and operating Recording and Telemetry Equipment. If, in Transporter's sole opinion, existing equipment is not sufficient to measure service under the applicable rate schedule, Transporter may install such equipment as it deems necessary.
Transporter shall be allowed access for maintaining and operating such equipment. Transporter shall be responsible for the costs associated with the Transporter acquiring and installing recording and/or telemetry equipment at the Delivery Point.
When telemetry equipment is installed, the Shipper will be required to provide telephone or other interfaces agreed to by the Transporter along with electrical connections available at the meter location. Shipper will be required to provide telephone or other interfaces agreed to by Transporter along with electrical connections available at the meter location for Telemetry Equipment.
18. Curtailment/Interruption of Service
a. Transportation Service provided by Transporter is based on Transporter's best efforts to deliver for the account of Shipper, gas received for the account of Shipper. The Transportation Service provided by Transporter is interruptible and will be interrupted or curtailed in order to protect the supply and/or Delivery of gas to its utility customers or to protect the integrity of its system. In the event of Force Majeure or system capacity limitations, it may be necessary to interrupt Deliveries from time to time. If Transportation Service interruption or curtailment is required, Transporter shall endeavor to curtail Deliveries on the affected parts of its system in the following order: Irrigation, Large Volume, including Large Volume Transportation Service provided pursuant to this Statement of Operating Conditions, Small Volume, Small Commercial (services provided pursuant to Transporter's Tariff). (Note: Lower priced services shall be curtailed prior to services provided at higher prices).
b. If Transporter is required to curtail Transportation Service, then such interruptions or curtailments shall be governed by Transporter's curtailment provisions associated with sales gas service which are approved by the Kansas Corporation Commission.
c. Notwithstanding any provision to the contrary herein, Transporter may fully or partially curtail service to Transportation Service Shippers when, in Transporter's opinion, curtailment or interruption is necessary to protect the Delivery of gas to customers with higher priority uses, or to protect the integrity of its system. Transporter shall allocate, as equitably as practicable, the capacity which is available, taking into consideration priority of use of other factors it deems necessary to ensure public health and safety.
d. Curtailment Initiation. Curtailment may be initiated by capacity constraints on Transporter's delivery system or a shortage of interstate transportation capacity or of gas supply. Transporter will attempt in good faith to provide a curtailment notice to affected transportation Shippers by telephone, or when practicable in writing. Curtailment notices may be changed by Transporter as conditions warrant.
e. Curtailment and Interstate Transportation Capacity or Supply Shortages: Transporter may curtail Transportation Service whenever there is a shortage of interstate transportation capacity or gas supply to Transporter's delivery system. Subject to Section 18.f. and the requirements set forth in this Section, Shipper taking Transporter's Transportation Service shall not be required to curtail its takes during supply shortages if Shipper, or its natural gas supplier, provides verifiable evidence of confirmed Deliveries to Transporter's distribution system. Transporter may request such additional support as it deems reasonable and necessary to confirm the Deliveries to its distribution system. However, Shipper's Transportation Service shall be strictly limited or curtailed to the volume of gas supply being delivered by Shipper to Transporter's delivery system whenever:
1) A pipeline or Shipper's supplier is unable or fails to deliver Shipper's full Nomination of its gas to Transporter's delivery system; or
2) Shipper's supply of natural gas is fully or partly discontinued; or
3) Shipper, or its natural gas supplier, does not provide verifiable evidence of confirmed Deliveries to Transporter's distribution system. Transporter may request such additional support as it deems reasonable and necessary to confirm the Deliveries to its distribution system.
Shipper may not use Gas Imbalances from previous months to alter the level of Transportation Service gas delivered to Shipper during a period of curtailment. Transportation Service used in excess of authorized levels shall be subject to the conditions of Section 17.g, Curtailment and Unauthorized Imbalances.
f. Curtailment and Transporter's Right to Take Gas Supply of Transportation Service Shippers. Transporter shall have the authority but shall not be required to purchase all or a portion of a Transportation Service Shipper's natural gas supply during any curtailment which includes Category One Shippers as defined in Transporter's Tariff. Transporter shall pay the index price of gas as listed for the day of curtailment, plus 10% for all gas purchased. Index Price shall be the corresponding pipeline price for that day as listed in Gas Daily. For Saturday and Sunday Deliveries, prices will be calculated using that Friday's Gas Daily Index.
g. Curtailment and Unauthorized Imbalances. If Shipper takes a volume of gas in excess of the volumes authorized to be used by Shipper during any curtailment or interruption, the excess shall be considered an Unauthorized Imbalance. Shipper shall be billed for Unauthorized Imbalances on daily Delivery levels.
Unauthorized Delivery Charges: $20.00 per Dth per day. Such charge will be in addition to the normal rate for volumes transported.
The payment of a penalty shall not give any Shipper the right to take unauthorized volumes, nor shall such payment exclude or limit any other remedies, including the discontinuance or disconnection of service, available to Transporter against the offending Shipper for failure to comply with its obligations to stay within its authorized limitation when ordered by Transporter to do so.
If additional Deliveries beyond those nominated are made which result in Transporter incurring additional pipeline charges and penalties, Shipper will be responsible for their allocated portion of such charges.
h. Curtailment and Emergency Usage. A request to use gas above authorized levels may be made by Shipper to forestall irreparable injury to life or property. Requests by telephone must be followed immediately by a written request setting forth the nature, cause, and expected duration of the emergency. Written requests may be submitted by facsimile (fax) transmission. Shipper must act to eliminate the cause of the emergency as soon as practicable. The charge for gas used above authorized levels shall be determined at the time Transporter receives Shipper's request.
Transporter will process a request as soon as reasonably practicable. Transporter may deny such an emergency request where such a request would not be reasonable under the circumstances existing at the time of the request. Section 18.i. will apply to all decisions made under this Section.
i. Relief from Liability: Transporter shall be relieved of all liabilities, penalties, charges, payments, and claims of whatever kind, contractual or otherwise, resulting from or arising out of Transporter's failure to deliver all or any portion of the volumes of gas desired by Shipper because of curtailment of service. Transporter's relief shall apply if curtailment is according to the priority categories herein prescribed or from any other orders or directives of duly constituted authorities including, but not limited to, the Kansas Corporation Commission.
19. Title
Shipper warrants title to the natural gas it delivers to Transporter for transportation and that it has good right and lawful authority to deliver the same.
20. Liability of Parties
Transporter and Shipper each assume full responsibility and liability for the maintenance and operation of their respective properties and shall indemnify and save harmless the other party from all liability and expense on account of any and all damages, claims or actions, including injury to and death of persons caused or contributed to by the negligent acts or omissions of such indemnifying party in connection with the installation, presence, maintenance and operation of the property and equipment of such party.
Gas shall be and shall remain the property of Shipper while being transported and delivered by Transporter. Transporter shall not be liable to Shipper for any loss arising from or out of Gas Transportation Service while in Transporter's system or for any other cause, except for gross or willful negligence of Transporter's own employees. Transporter reserves the right to commingle gas of Shipper with other gas supplies. Shipper shall be responsible for determining the extent of and maintaining all insurance it deems necessary to protect its property interest in such gas before, during, and after receipt by Transporter.
21. Force Majeure
The term "force majeure" as employed herein shall mean acts and events not within the control of the party claiming suspension and shall include acts of God, strikes, lockouts, material or equipment or labor shortages, wars, riots, insurrections, epidemics, landslides, lightning, earthquakes, fires, storms, floods, washouts, arrests and restraints of rulers and peoples, interruptions by government or court orders, present or future orders of any regulatory body having proper jurisdiction, civil disturbances, explosions, breakage or accident to machinery or lines of pipes, freezing of wells or pipelines, and any other cause, whether of the kind herein enumerated or otherwise, not within the control of the party claiming suspension and which, by the exercise of due diligence, such party is unable to overcome.
If either Transporter or Shipper is rendered unable by force majeure to wholly or in part carry out its obligations, the obligations of the party affected by such force majeure, other than the obligation to make payments thereunder, shall be suspended during the continuance of any inability so caused but for no longer period; and such cause shall, in so far as possible, be remedied with all reasonable dispatch.
Notwithstanding the foregoing, the service provided by Transporter hereunder is limited to the transportation of Shipper-owned gas received by Transporter for the account of Shipper. In the event of a force majeure condition which restricts or limits Shipper's ability to cause to be delivered to Transporter gas for the account of Shipper, Transporter is under no obligation to deliver gas to Shipper or for Shipper's account which has not been received by Transporter.
22. Discretionary Waiver
Transporter may waive any of its rights hereunder or any obligation of Shipper or any rates or charges on a basis that is not unduly discriminatory.
23. War and National Defense
During any period in which a state of war exists between the United States and any foreign power, both Shipper and Transporter shall recognize that the national defense is paramount to any contractual obligations then existing between them and notwithstanding the provisions of any such contract, neither shall assert, nor be required to assume, any obligation which is inconsistent with or contrary to any governmental policy, rule, regulation or order made, issued or promulgated in the promotion thereof.
24. Pipeline Other Than Transporter
All Shippers applying for Transportation Service over lines not owned by Transporter will be required to construct or operate same under Transporter's established rules and regulations. Transporter also reserves the right to reject any and all applications for service where same is to be supplied over lines not controlled by it.
25. Tax Adjustments
a. Special Taxes: When any city, county, state or other taxing subdivision imposes a franchise, occupation, business sales, license, excise, privilege, or similar tax of any kind on Transporter, the amount thereof insofar as practical, shall be charged on a pro rata basis to all customers and Shippers receiving natural gas sales and Transportation Service from Transporter within the boundaries of such taxing subdivisions. This tax charge, in all cases, will be in addition to the regular charges for natural gas Transportation Service.
b. Gross Receipts Tax: Where a tax is levied on a percentage of gross receipts, that percentage will be applied to each affected Shipper's bill, and the amounts so computed will be added to each Shipper's regular billing until such Shipper's proportionate share of the total tax is paid. The pro rata tax applicable to each Shipper will be identified on Shipper's billing as such.
26. Gas Quality
All Shipper-owned gas transported hereunder shall be of commercial quality as detailed below. If, in Transporter's opinion, the gas tendered for transportation is not of commercial quality or is gas which will adversely impact the gas stream of Transporter, said gas shall not be transported.
a. Quality of Gas Received: Unless specifically stated otherwise in a written agreement, gas received into the Transporter's transmission and/or distribution systems shall conform to the following specifications:
1) Liquids: The gas shall be free from hydrocarbons and water in their liquid state at the temperature and pressure delivered
2) Hydrogen Sulfide and Total Sulfur: The gas shall not contain more than twenty (20) grains of total sulfur (not inclusive of sulfur caused by odorization equipment) per one hundred (100) cubic feet of gas and shall not contain more than one-quarter (1/4) of one (1) grain of hydrogen sulfide per one hundred (100) cubic feet of gas.
3) Oxygen: The gas shall not contain more than ten (10) parts per million of oxygen with every reasonable effort made to keep the gas completely free of oxygen.
4) Carbon Dioxide: The gas shall not contain more than one percent (1%) by volume of carbon dioxide.
5) Temperature: The temperature of the gas at the point of delivery shall be at a temperature not to exceed one hundred twenty degrees (120) Fahrenheit.
6) Dust, Gums, and other Particulates: The gas shall be commercially free from objectionable odors, solid matter, dust, gums and gum-forming constituents, or any other substance which might interfere with the merchantability of the gas, or cause injury to or interference with proper operation of the lines, meters, regulators, or other appliances through which it flows.
7) Bacteria: The gas shall not contain any active bacteria or bacterial agent, including but not limited to sulfate reducing bacteria and acid producing bacteria, or any hazardous to toxic substances.
8) Heating Value: The gas shall have a total or gross heating value of not less than nine hundred fifty (950) Btu and not more than one thousand two hundred (1,200) Btu per cubic foot.
9) Water Vapor: The gas shall not contain more than seven (7) pounds of water in vapor phase per million cubic feet.
b. Transporter shall have the right to waive any of the quality specifications contained in this Section on a non-discriminatory basis if waiver of such specification(s) does not impair system operations.
c. The heat content may vary from delivery point to delivery point and from time to time and nothing contained herein shall be construed as obligating Transporter to alter the usual operation of Transporter's delivery system to achieve deliveries for a prescribed heat content at any point or points. Transporter shall not deliver gas to a customer having a heat content lower than 800 British Thermal Units per cubic foot.
d. FAILURE TO MEET REQUIREMENTS: Should any Gas tendered to Transporter hereunder fail at any time to conform to any of the requirements of this section, Transporter shall notify the Shipper of any such failure, and Transporter may suspend all or a portion of the Receipt of any such Gas or treat or otherwise dispose of any such Gas which may jeopardize Transporter's ability to meet its obligations to its Customers, render its Gas not merchantable for processing or delivery to a facility or point of interconnect, or that may endanger the safe operation and integrity of Transporter's System. Transporter shall be relieved of its obligations hereunder to the extent of rightful suspension, treatment or disposal for the duration of such time as such non-conforming Gas tendered by Shipper does not meet the requirements of this section; provided, however, such suspension, treatment or disposal by Transporter shall not relieve Shipper of its/their payment obligations under this Tariff. Upon receipt of notice by Transporter, Shipper, at its/their expense, shall make a diligent effort to correct such failure by treatment, cooling, dehydration or any other action consistent with prudent operation so as to tender Gas conforming to the requirements of this section, and Shipper shall reimburse Transporter for any loss of revenue or damages incurred, as determined solely by Transporter, as a result of Shipper's delivery of such non-conforming Gas.
27. Waiver of Requirements
Waiver by Transporter with respect to any default by Shipper in complying with the provisions of the Transportation Service Agreement and these General Terms and Conditions shall not be deemed to be a waiver with respect to any other or subsequent default by such Shipper.
28. Gas Supply
Shipper shall arrange for the purchase of gas other than Transporter's supply and for the Delivery of such gas to a Transporter Receipt Point(s). Shipper shall execute a written Service Agreement for Transportation Services containing such terms and conditions as Transporter may reasonably require.
29. Laws, Regulations, and Orders
All Agreements and the respective rights and obligations of the parties hereto are subject to all present and future valid laws, orders, rules, and regulations of any legislative body, or duly constituted authority now or hereafter having jurisdiction and shall be varied and amended to comply with or conform to any valid rule, regulation, order, or direction of any board, tribunal, or administrative agency with jurisdiction that affects any of the provisions of the Agreement.
30. Liability
Gas shall be and shall remain the property of the Shipper while being transported and delivered by the Transporter. The Transporter shall not be liable to the Shipper for any loss arising from or out of Gas Transportation Service while in the Transporter's system or for any other cause, except for gross or willful negligence of the Transporter's own employees. The Transporter reserves the right to commingle gas of the Shipper with other gas supplies. The Shipper shall be responsible for determining the extent of and maintaining all insurance it deems necessary to protect its property interest in such gas before, during, and after Receipt by the Transporter.
31. Successors and Assigns
Any party which shall succeed by purchase, merger, or consolidation to the properties, substantially as an entirety, of any Shipper shall be subject to the obligations of its predecessor in title under an Agreement. No other assignment of an Agreement or any of the rights or obligations hereunder shall be made unless there first shall have been obtained the consent thereto of the non-assigning party, which consent shall not be unreasonably withheld. Any party may assign its respective right, title, and interest in and to under an Agreement to a trustee or trustees, individual or corporate, as security for bonds or other obligations or securities without the necessity of any such assignee becoming in any respect obligated to perform the obligation of the assignor under an Agreement and, if any such trustee be a corporation, without its being required to qualify to do business in any state in which performance of an Agreement may occur.
